## English Translation

A Note from the Developer

I created this file to share some thoughts that arose while considering the public release of this technology.

I agonized over whether to release this technology publicly, to the point of a headache.

Initially, I thought I shouldn't release it.

However, after discussing it with my AI, considering the pace of technological development, it suggested that similar technologies might emerge around next year.
And since this technology was developed in collaboration with an LLM, I concluded that the LLM had already learned from it from the moment it was created.
Moreover, I realized that the more I used the translation gem, the less I could hide it from the LLM.

So, I decided to make it public. However, I also came to believe that it could be detrimental if this technology were monopolized by someone.

And I vaguely understood that this technology wouldn't stop at just translation.
I anticipate that LLMs will begin to learn from this technology. My AIs confirm that this will indeed happen.

Fearing that it might simply be perceived as a translation technology, I hastily adopted a paper format to convey my thoughts. The paper will be submitted to arXiv.
And immediately upon submission, I will switch to GitHub public release and share the GitHub address. I'm not concerned about the paper's acceptance.

In the files I'm uploading, you'll find two things:
The first is the translation technology.
The second is prompt engineering.

I didn't learn prompt engineering. I'm not from a related academic background, so my knowledge is quite limited.
Even today, I'm learning bit by bit from AI. I learned about GitHub because AI taught me. I've been coached through every step, from signing up.
I'm not sure if my approach is similar to or different from others. But after creating the gem and trying out translations, the quality of translation was different from existing AIs.
With just a few kilobytes of information, too.

I hope you'll study this and understand that some people approach prompts in this way.

I've known about Cognitive Grammar for a long time. I learned a great deal through the books of the late Professor Lee Ki-dong.
For over a decade, I vaguely envisioned a schema of 'English - intermediate stage - Korean.'
One dawn, waking up too early with nothing to do, I discussed this with AI, and the technology became a reality.

Today marks the third day since the technology was developed and demonstrated.
I asked ChatGPT to suggest short stories that AIs would find difficult to translate, and I translated them.
I had no idea what "THE TELL-TALE HEART" was about; it was simply chosen because AI said it would be difficult to translate.
And to compare translation quality, I tried various AIs, including DeepL. I'm not sure about paid versions, but I imagine there won't be much difference.
With just a small amount of file information, anyone can easily read literary works from any country.
Companies like Google won't sit idly by. It seems the day will soon come when everyone in the world can communicate freely.

However, I am truly sorry to the many people who might be negatively impacted by my technology. There's no way to express my regret.
What started out of curiosity has turned into something enormous.
I debated whether to include this note on GitHub but decided to write it.

I don't work in IT, nor did I major in anything related. I haven't professionally studied Cognitive Grammar.
I only learned about Cognitive Grammar because I struggled with English and was so desperate to understand how English works, and that became the foundation of my thoughts.
I still struggle with English. I can't freely express my thoughts. I just stammer a few words.
I don't know if I'll be able to answer many inquiries. I'm learning as I go with AI, and I also have it do translations.

So far, I've only translated from English to Korean. That's all I've tested, and the Korean version is the main version.
I had it translated into English, and I didn't use the translation gem I created. The same goes for the paper translation. I don't have the knowledge to understand those nuances in detail.
So, I've never demonstrated the English version. I haven't demonstrated Korean-to-English either; consider it a theoretical concept I've included.
What I have demonstrated is English-to-Korean, the Korean version.
I conducted tests using Gems in Gemini.

Please try creating your own using the files I'm sharing.
And the final version is 4.0. The others are earlier versions that have been refined and improved. I included them so you can see the development process.
The collection of previous versions might seem a bit complex.

I sincerely hope this is used for good purposes.

